:::

A piecewise polynomial approach to model the data from @fig-global-polynomial.

:::

It turns out that we can make sure that the different fitted curves can connect at the ends and that they do that smoothly. This is done via a technique called splines which yeild better results and are more mathematically elegant.

## Spline Functions {#sec-splines}

Let’s assume we use piecewise cubic polynomials in the regional curve fits. To make the curves connect, we can add additional features that isolate local areas of $x$ via a new feature column such as $h(x - \xi)^3$ where

$$
h(u)  =
\begin{cases} x & \text{if $u > 0$,}
\\
0 & \text{if $u \le 0$.}
\end{cases}
$$

and $\xi$ defines one of the boundary points.

This zeros out parts of the predictor’s range that are greater than $\xi$. A smooth, continuous model would include a global polynomial expansion (i.e., $x$, $x^2$, and $x^3$) and these partial features for each value that defines the regions (these breakpoints, denoted with $\xi$, are called _knots_^[Actually, they are the _interior knots_. The full set of knots includes the minimum and maximum values of $x$ in the training set.]). For example, if a model has three regions,  the basis expansion has 3 + 2 = 5 feature columns. For the fossil data, a three region model with knots at $\xi_1 = 107$ and $\xi_2 = 114$ would have model terms

$$
y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_i + \beta_2x^2 + \beta_3x^3 + \beta_4h(x_i - 107)^3 + \beta_5h(x_i - 114)^3 + \epsilon_i
$$ {#eq-simple-spline}

The model fit, with the default interior knots, shown in @fig-simple-spline looks acceptable. As with global polynomials, there is a significant increase in the confidence interval width as the model begins to extrapolate slightly beyond the data used to fit the model.  

::: {#fig-simple-spline}

::: {.figure-content}

